Gnuplot¶

Gnuplot is a portable command-line driven graphing utility for Linux, OS/2, MS Windows, OSX, VMS, and many other platforms. The source code is copyrighted but freely distributed. It was originally created to allow scientists and students to visualize mathematical functions and data interactively, but has grown to support many non-interactive uses such as web scripting. It is also used as a plotting engine by third-party applications like Octave. Gnuplot has been supported and under active development since 1986 (see also Wikipedia).

Gnuplot is distributed with a large set of demonstration scripts. Further below are samples of canvas output from some of the demos. Details: pdf_manual.

Using in jFriCAS¶

If you have installed gnuplot and set the link to the gnuplot javascript library as described in the install section, then you may use Gnuplot in the jFriCAS Jupyter notebook with the (fake) FriCAS command

)gnuplot <commands>

There are, however, some minor restrictions compared to the terminal version. These differences will be explained below. First we will show how the jfricas kernel deals with the )gnuplot cell input. The corresponding Python code in the jfricas kernel reads:

cmdl = code[len(gplot):].lstrip().split('\n')
cmd = ';'.join(cmdl)
uid = "plot"+"".join(str(uuid.uuid4()).split('-'))
gcmd = 'gnuplot -e "set term canvas name {0};{1}"'.format("'"+uid+"'",cmd)
gcp = run(gcmd, stdout=PIPE, stderr=STDOUT, timeout=shell_timeout, shell=True)
gjs = gcp.stdout.decode()
gdata['text/html'] = gptpl.format(gpjsf, uid, gjs, uid)
display_data = {'data':gdata, 'metadata':{}}

Therefore, each line in the cell represents a single command (cmdl). Then all lines will be joined by a semicolon (;) to form the whole Gnuplot command (cmd). This command will then be sent to the Gnuplot engine which will return the result as a HTML5 canvas. The canvas id is uid and will be eventually displayed.

This means that no file images will be produced (like png,jpg etc.). If you like to have an image file, you may do a mouse right-click in the canvas area, and then select Save Image As ....

Differences (dos and don’ts)¶

  • Use single quotes whenever possible.

  • Double quotes have to be escaped by \.

  • Don’t use set terminal (preconfigured).

  • Don’t use set title (embedded canvas).

  • Don’t use comments # (may invalidate the whole command).

  • Use the notebook markdown capabilities for text explanations instead.

  • Don’t use Gnuplot’s line continuation (\).

  • Avoid concatenating commands by ; if possible.

  • Use one line per command (preferred).

The examples following will give an impression of how it will work well. In connection with FriCAS, it is best used by producing a datafile with any suitable method (e.g. GnuDraw, Plot, Plot3d etc.) or create the files on the fly by using the shell (!).

Plot a single data file¶

Reference

RIP_tutorial

)version

Value = "FriCAS 1.3.5 compiled at Sun Feb  3 18:21:59 UTC 2019"

!cat <<_EOF > /tmp/gp.dat
# Prototype of a gnuplot data set
# gp.dat
# X -   X^2 -    2*X -    Random
0       0        0        5
1       1        2        15
1.4142  2        2.8284   1
2       4        4        30
3       9        6        26.46
3.1415  9.8696   6.2832   39.11
4       16       8        20
4.5627  20.8182  9.1254   17
5.0     25.0     10.0     25.50
6       36       12       0.908
_EOF

)gnuplot
filename='/tmp/gp.dat'
plot filename

)gnuplot
filename='/tmp/gp.dat'
plot filename,sin(x)

)gnuplot
filename='/tmp/gp.dat'
plot filename using 2:4

)gnuplot
filename='/tmp/gp.dat'
splot filename using 1:2:3

)gnuplot
filename='/tmp/gp.dat'
plot filename using 1:4 with linespoint

)gnuplot
filename='/tmp/gp.dat'
plot for [col = 2:4] filename using 1:col w lp

)gnuplot
filename='/tmp/gp.dat'
set grid
plot for [col = 2:4] filename using 1:col w lp

Gnuplot Demos¶

Ref: gnuplot.sourceforge.net/demo

)gnuplot
set key left box
set samples 50
set style data points

plot [-10:10] sin(x),atan(x),cos(atan(x))

)gnuplot
set key right nobox
set samples 100
plot [-pi/2:pi] cos(x),-(sin(x) > sin(x+1) ? sin(x) : sin(x+1))

)gnuplot
set key left box
set samples 200
plot [-3:5] asin(x),acos(x)

)gnuplot plot [-30:20] besj0(x)*0.12e1 with impulses, (x**besj0(x))-2.5 with points

)gnuplot set samples 400
plot [-10:10] real(sin(x)**besj0(x))

)gnuplot
set key bmargin center horizontal
plot [-5*pi:5*pi] [-5:5] real(tan(x)/atan(x)), 1/x

)gnuplot
set key left box
set autoscale
set samples 800
plot [-30:20] sin(x*20)*atan(x)

slice(x,y) = (x**2+y**2 < 10.0) ? 1.0 : (x**2+y**2 > 300.0) ? NaN : sin(abs(atan2(x,y)))
sinc2(x,y) = sin(sqrt(x**2+y**2))/sqrt(x**2+y**2)
flatten(x,y) = sqrt(x**2+y**2)/5.
F(x,y) =  sinc2(x,y) * slice(x,y) * flatten(x,y)
